## Step 2: Design the Content Architecture

### Slide Structure Template

Every deck should follow this narrative shape:

```
1. TITLE SLIDE — Deck name, presenter, date/context
2. AGENDA / OVERVIEW — What we'll cover (optional for short decks)
3–N. BODY SLIDES — Core content (varies by deck type)
N-1. SUMMARY / KEY TAKEAWAYS — Distill main points
N. CTA / NEXT STEPS — What happens next, or Q&A
```

### Per-Slide Blueprint

For each slide, define:
- **Headline**: A single declarative sentence (not a label). E.g., "Revenue grew 40% YoY" not "Revenue"
- **Key Point**: 1–3 supporting bullets maximum
- **Visual**: Chart, image, icon cluster, stat callout — never text-only
- **Speaker Notes**: 2–4 sentences the presenter can use

### Content Principles

- **One idea per slide** — if you need a comma in the title, split it
- **Headlines tell the story** — reading only headlines should convey the full narrative
- **Show, don't list** — replace bullet lists with visuals wherever possible
- **Data beats claims** — back assertions with numbers when possible

